@startuml application_layer

package "Application Layer" {

    ' ==========================================
    ' CORE ENGINE WRAPPERS
    ' ==========================================
    class Game {
        - isRunning : bool
        - window : Window*
        - gameLoop : GameLoop*
        - sceneManager : SceneManager*
        + init(title: string, width: int, height: int): bool
        + run(): void
        + stop(): void
        + clean(): void
    }

    class Window {
        - width : int
        - height : int
        - title : string
        + init(title: string, w: int, h: int): bool
        + beginDraw(): void
        + endDraw(): void
        + close(): void
        + isShouldClose(): bool
    }

    class GameLoop {
        - accumulator : float
        - isRunning : bool
        + run(sceneManager: SceneManager&): void
        + stop(): void
    }

    ' ==========================================
    ' STATE MANAGEMENT (Composite/Stack Pattern)
    ' ==========================================
    class SceneManager {
        - stateStack : std::vector<IGameState*>
        + pushState(state: IGameState*): void
        + popState(): void
        + changeState(state: IGameState*): void
        + update(dt: float): void
        + render(alpha: float): void
        + clear(): void
    }

    interface IGameState {
        + {abstract} onEnter(): bool
        + {abstract} onExit(): bool
        + {abstract} update(dt: float): void
        + {abstract} render(alpha: float): void
    }

    class SplashState {
        + update(dt: float): void
        + render(alpha: float): void
    }
    class TitleState {
        + update(dt: float): void
        + render(alpha: float): void
    }
    class MenuState {
        + update(dt: float): void
        + render(alpha: float): void
    }
    class PlayState {
        + update(dt: float): void
        + render(alpha: float): void
    }
    class PauseState {
        + update(dt: float): void
        + render(alpha: float): void
    }
    class TransitionState {
        + update(dt: float): void
        + render(alpha: float): void
    }
    class GameOverState {
        + update(dt: float): void
        + render(alpha: float): void
    }

}

package "UI Layer" {
    ' ==========================================
    ' USER INTERFACE CONTROLS
    ' ==========================================
    class HUD {
        + render(score: int, coins: int, world: string, lives: int, timer: float): void
    }

    class Menu {
        - items : std::vector<string>
        - selectedIndex : int
        + moveUp(): void
        + moveDown(): void
        + select(): void
        + render(): void
    }

    class NumberRenderer {
        + static draw(number: int, pos: Vector2D): void
    }
}

' ==========================================
' RELATIONSHIPS & DEPENDENCIES
' ==========================================

Game *-- Window : owns >
Game *-- GameLoop : owns >
Game *-- SceneManager : owns >

SceneManager o-- IGameState : manages stack of >

IGameState <|.. SplashState
IGameState <|.. TitleState
IGameState <|.. MenuState
IGameState <|.. PlayState
IGameState <|.. PauseState
IGameState <|.. TransitionState
IGameState <|.. GameOverState

PlayState ..> HUD : renders >
MenuState ..> Menu : controls >
HUD ..> NumberRenderer : uses >
Menu ..> NumberRenderer : uses >

note left of SceneManager
  Uses a Stack to allow Overlays.
  Example: PauseState is pushed 
  ON TOP of PlayState, allowing 
  PlayState to remain in memory.
end note

note right of GameLoop
  Implements the Fixed-Timestep
  logic (accumulating dt) and
  passes interpolation alpha
  to the active state's render.
end note

note left of Window
  Wraps Raylib lifecycle functions.
  beginDraw() -> BeginDrawing() + ClearBackground()
  endDraw() -> EndDrawing()
end note

@enduml

Key Architectural Takeaways (Raylib Version)
Game & Hardware Abstraction: The Game class acts as 
the top-level orchestrator. It sets up the Raylib environment 
through the Window wrapper (which manages InitWindow() and CloseWindow()), 
initializes the SceneManager, and hands control over to the GameLoop. 
This encapsulates Raylib's global lifecycle functions away from your 
core game logic.

The State Stack (SceneManager): Instead of simple boolean flags 
or a single active state, this layer uses a Push/Pop Stack. 
This is what allows the PauseState to be drawn on top of the 
PlayState without having to destroy or reload the game level. 
When the player unpauses, the stack simply calls popState(), and 
the gameplay resumes exactly where it left off.

Global Rendering Context: Because Raylib utilizes a global 
graphics context, you no longer need to pass a Renderer 
object through every function. State and UI classes simply 
call their internal render() methods, which safely utilize 
Raylib's native drawing functions (like DrawRectangle, DrawTexture, etc.) directly.


The UI Decoupling: The UI components (HUD, Menu) are stateless renderers. 
They do not store the player's score or lives. 
Instead, the PlayState pulls that data from the active 
player entity and passes it directly into the HUD::render() method.

Fixed-Timestep Bridge: The GameLoop is where the alpha 
variable (used for rendering interpolation between two physics frames) 
is calculated. It passes this alpha down through the SceneManager into 
the specific IGameState::render() method, ensuring smooth visual 
movement at any framerate while your physics update at a fixed rate.